            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> You're right that they're running 0 (since that's the \"default value\" for the numeric types).\r\n>\r\n> However, typically we'd use -1 as an error code for numeric types\r\n\r\nYeah, now I see:\r\n![image](https://github.com/cython/cython/assets/827060/715f6b71-4fb7-40c6-a6f2-3ef2f3752226)\r\n\r\nFunctions returning numbers are propagating exception by default via `-1` and pointers/python objects propagate exceptions by default via `0`.\r\n\r\nA question, is there any complication simple to propagate for fused types via `0`? It's not 100% consistent but i consider it still more straightforward than having special logic for `.pxd` files or having two values for propagation (`0` and `-1`)?",
